CSS :== CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is a stylesheet language used to control how HTML content looks on a webpage—things 
like colors, layouts, fonts, spacing, and responsiveness. It separates design from structure, making websites easier to maintain.

1. CSS1 (1996)
Introduced by the World Wide Web Consortium
Basic styling: fonts, colors, spacing, alignment
Very limited but laid the foundation.

2. CSS2 (1998)
Added more advanced features:
Positioning (absolute, relative)
Z-index (layering)
Media types (screen, print)
Improved layout control.

3. CSS2.1 (2011)
Refined version of CSS2
Fixed bugs and improved compatibility across browsers
Became the stable standard for years.

4. CSS3 (from ~2011 onward)
Not a single version—split into modules
Major improvements:
Animations & transitions
Flexbox and Grid layouts
Rounded corners, shadows, gradients
Media queries (responsive design)
Modern web design relies heavily on CSS3 features.
